\par
\par
\par
                                    respond to the driving force exerted on it. However, re\u64258?ecting our still incomplete understanding of\par
                                    ways in which dislocations move, mobility functions presently employed in DDD simulations entail\par
                                    simpli\u64257?cations and approximations of limited or, worse still, unknown accuracy and applicability. Here\par
                                    we introduce a data-driven approach in which the dislocation mobility function is modeled as a graph\par
                                    neural network (GNN) trained on large-scale MD simulations of crystal plasticity. We apply our\par
                                    proposed approach to predicting plastic strength of body-centered-cubic (BCC) metal tungsten and\par
                                    show that, once implemented in a DDD model, our GNN dislocation mobility function accurately\par
                                    reproduces the challenging tension/compression asymmetry of plastic \u64258?ow observed both in ground-\par
                                    truth MD simulations and in experiment. Furthermore, subsequently validated by MD simulations, the\par
                                    same function accurately predicts plastic response of tungsten under conditions not previously seen\par
                                    in training. By demonstrating its ability to learn relevant physics of dislocation motion, our DDD+ML\par
                                    approach opens a promising avenue to bringing \u64257?delity of DDD models closer in line with direct MD\par
                                    simulations at a much reduced computational cost.\par
